                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      Move to amend tapping law
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                               
	New Delhi, May 13: The government will bring amendments in Parliaments next session to regulate passive or off-the-air interception of phone conversations, the move prompted by the tapping row at the height of the IPL scandal.        
	The amendments, to be made in the Indian Telegraph Act, 1885, through a bill, will give legal sanctity to the governments passive tapping, while putting in place severe penalties if it is done by private players. The bill will also propose a panel under the Prime Ministers Office to oversee such tapping.        
	At present, the act allows tapping only of target-centric telephones  a phone security agencies suspect is being used by a person involved in criminal offences or activities affecting national security.        
	The issue of tapping had caused an uproar in Parliament last month after reports that the National Technical Research Organisation  a scientific body under the PMO  used phone interception equipment to listen in to conversations of prominent politicians.                                                                                                                                                           
